{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518105"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12876"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.04,0.03,0.09,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102219"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5318"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102219"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with increasing fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. He is admitted to hospital for an acute exacerbation of asthma complicated by a pulmonary bacterial infection. He was started on ceftriaxone four days ago. He has a medical history of hypertension and diabetes. Six months ago, he had a chest infection which was also treated with ceftriaxone. His current medications include prednisolone, azithromycin, salbutamol, and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His vital signs are within normal limits. It is noticed that he now has dark-coloured urine. His laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 101 g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocyte count: 6.7% (0.2-2%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 302 U/L (135-225)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 321 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 38.6 \u03bcmol/L (5-21)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIndirect bilirubin: 29 \u03bcmol/L (1-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPositive direct antiglobulin test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe laboratory findings were unremarkable when the patient was first admitted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drugs is most likely responsible for the haemolytic anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Azithromycin","Paracetamol","Salbutamol","Prednisolone","Ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with clinical and laboratory evidence of haemolytic anaemia. The dark-coloured urine, decreased haemoglobin, elevated reticulocyte count, raised lactate dehydrogenase, and increased indirect bilirubin are all consistent with haemolysis. The positive direct antiglobulin test (DAT) indicates an immune-mediated process, suggesting drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely culprit among the listed medications. This cephalosporin antibiotic is a well-documented cause of drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia. The patient\u0027s previous exposure to ceftriaxone six months ago likely sensitised his immune system, leading to antibody formation. Upon re-exposure, these antibodies triggered an immune response against red blood cells, causing haemolysis. The temporal relationship between ceftriaxone administration and the development of haemolysis further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E, a macrolide antibiotic, is rarely associated with immune haemolytic anaemia. While it can cause other adverse effects, it is not a common cause of drug-induced haemolysis and would be an unlikely explanation for this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E (acetaminophen) is a commonly used analgesic and antipyretic that can cause hepatotoxicity in overdose but is very rarely associated with immune haemolytic anaemia. It would be an unlikely cause of this patient\u0027s haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-2 adrenergic agonist used as a bronchodilator for asthma, is not associated with immune haemolytic anaemia. Its adverse effects typically include tachycardia, tremor, and hypokalaemia, but not haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E, a corticosteroid, is actually used in the treatment of immune haemolytic anaemia rather than being a cause. It suppresses immune responses and would be more likely to ameliorate than precipitate an immune-mediated haemolytic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia involves immediate discontinuation of the offending drug, supportive care, and in severe cases, corticosteroids or intravenous immunoglobulin. The patient should be counselled to avoid ceftriaxone in the future, and this should be clearly documented as a drug allergy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ceftriaxone can cause drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia, particularly in patients with previous exposure.","Drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia presents with anaemia, elevated reticulocytes, raised LDH, hyperbilirubinaemia, and a positive direct antiglobulin test.","Previous sensitisation to a medication increases the risk of immune-mediated reactions upon re-exposure."],"references":["Boil\u00e8ve A, Gavaud A, Grignano E, et al. Acute and fatal cephalosporin-induced autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 2021;87(4):2152-2156. doi:10.1111/bcp.14612","Hill QA, Stamps R, Massey E, Grainger JD, Provan D, Hill A. Guidelines on the management of drug-induced immune and secondary autoimmune, haemolytic anaemia. Br J Haematol 2017;177:208-220.","Garratty G. Immune hemolytic anemia associated with drug therapy. Blood Rev. 2010 Jul-Sep;24(4-5):143-50. doi: 10.1016/j.blre.2010.06.004. Epub 2010 Jul 21. PMID: 20650555."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T20:02:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T20:04:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5318"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102219"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","